04172nam a22007095i 9780674059207DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212011mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740592077 a10.4159/97806740592072doi  a(DE-B1597)583419  a(OCoLC)1253313022  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a305.80091 aBornstein, George, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Colors of Zion :bBlacks, Jews, and Irish from 1845 to 1945 /cGeorge Bornstein. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Races -- t2. Diasporas and Nationalisms -- t3. Melting Pots -- t4. Popular and Institutional Cultures -- t5. The Gathering Storm: Th e 1930s and World War II -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis comparative study focuses on three groups often seen as antagonistic—Blacks, Jews, and Irish. Resolutely aware of past tensions, Bornstein argues that the pendulum has swung too far in that direction and that it is time to recover the history of lost connections and cooperation among the groups. The chronological range stretches from Frederick Douglass’s tour of Ireland during the Great Famine of the 1840s through the 1940s with the catastrophe of World War II. The study ends with the concept of the Righteous Gentile commemorated at the Israeli Holocaust Memorial, Yad Vashem--non-Jews who during the Holocaust risked their own lives to rescue Jews from the horror of the Holocaust. Bornstein expands the term here to include all those Irish, Jewish, or African American figures who fought against narrow identification only with their own group and instead championed a wider and more humane vision of a shared humanity that sees hybridity rather than purity and love rather than resentment. The identity politics and culture wars of recent decades often made recognizing those positive qualities problematic. But with the election of a mixed-race president who himself embodies mixture and mutual respect (and who famously described himself as a “mutt”), the shallow and arbitrary nature of narrow identity politics become evident. This study recuperates strong voices from the past of all three groups in order to let them speak for themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aBlacksxRace identity. 0aEthnic relationsxHistory. 0aIrish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aIrishxEthnic identity. 0aJewsxIdentity. 0aRace relations in literature. 0aRacismxHistory. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674059207423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674059207.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK